      "\n   ```\n   fderiv F (r‚āĀ, t‚āĀ) (v, 1) = fderiv F (r‚āā, t‚āā) (v, 1)\n   ```\n3. The derivative is linear in the direction, so this is similar to saying that `fderiv F (r‚āĀ, t‚āĀ)` and `fderiv F (r‚āā, t‚āā)` have the same restriction to the subspace `{(v, 1) : v ‚ąą ‚ĄĚ‚ĀŅ}`.\n\nBut since `(v, 1)` and `(v', 1)` can generate the entire space when varying `v`, perhaps it is not possible unless the derivatives are the same everywhere?\n\nAlternatively, perhaps:\n4. The function `f : (r, t) ‚Ü¶ fderiv F (r, t)` is constant because it has the same value on a sufficiently large set. \n\nBut this would imply that `F` is linear. \n\nBut no: `F` could be quadratic, and the derivative would be changing. \n\nBut in our case, `fderiv F (r, t) (v, 1)` doesn't depend on `r, t`, which is very restrictive.\n\nLet me try instead:\n\nWe know that for any `v`, `fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1)` is actually independent of `r` and `t`. \n\nBut:\n```\nfderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1) = ‚ąāF/‚ąār (r, t) ‚čÖ v + ‚ąāF/‚ąāt (r, t)\n```\n\nSince `őīL(v)` is independent of `r` and `t`, we have:\n```\n‚ąāF/‚ąār (r, t) ‚čÖ v + ‚ąāF/‚ąāt (r, t) = ‚ąāF/‚ąār (r', t') ‚čÖ v + ‚ąāF/‚ąāt (r', t')\n```\nfor any `r, t, r', t'`.\n\nThus, if we take `v = 0`, we get `‚ąāF/‚ąāt (r, t)` is constant (independent of `r` and `t`). \n\nLet's call this constant `c`.\n\nSimilarly, taking `v = e_i`, we get `‚ąāF/‚ąār_i (r, t) + c = ‚ąāF/‚ąār_i (r', t') + c`, so `‚ąāF/‚ąār_i` is also independent of `r` and `t`. \n\nThus, let `g_i = ‚ąāF/‚ąār_i (0, 0)`.\n\nThen, for any `(r, t)` and any `v`, we have:\n```\nőīL(v) = ‚ąĎ i, g_i v_i + c\n```\n\nBut if we take `v = 0`, we get `őīL(0) = c`. But from `hőīL0`, `őīL(0) = 0`, so `c = 0`.\n\nThus:\n```\nőīL(v) = ‚ąĎ i, g_i v_i\n```\nwhich means `őīL(v) = ‚ü™g, v‚üę`, QED.\n\nBut we need to formalize this using `fderiv`.\n\n### Step 5: Formalization Approach\n\n1. Obtain `F : EuclideanSpace ‚ĄĚ (Fin n) √ó ‚ĄĚ ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ` from the hypothesis `h`.\n2. Since `őīL(v) = fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1)` for any `r, t`, we can use that the `0`-th component of `fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t)` (i.e., the derivative w.r.t. `t`) is constant. Similarly, the `i`-th component for `i ‚ąą Fin n` (i.e., the derivative w.r.t. `r_i`) is also constant.\n3. But in Lean, `fderiv` is a linear map, and the partial derivatives are coefficients in a basis. \n4. Alternatively, since `fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t)` is a linear map `(EuclideanSpace ‚ĄĚ (Fin n) √ó ‚ĄĚ) ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ`, and we know that for any `v : EuclideanSpace ‚ĄĚ (Fin n)`, `fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1)` is the same for any `(r, t)`, then perhaps we can write `fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, s) = s * c + ‚ü™g, v‚üę`, but we would need to deduce this. \n\nBut perhaps a simpler approach:\n\n- The condition implies that for any `v`, the function `G(r, t) = fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1)` is constant. But `G(r, t)` is differentiable with derivative `(d/dr G, d/dt G) = 0`, which can only happen if `F` is linear or has special properties. \n\nBut perhaps it's too messy.\n\nAnother approach is inspired by this: \n\nFor any `v`, `fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1)` is constant in `r, t`. \n\nThen, for any fixed `v`, the function `H(r, t) = F(r, t) + f(r, t)` has derivative zero in certain directions. \n\nActually, no. Maybe it's better to think like:\n\nThe difference of the derivative evaluated at `(r, t)` and `(r', t')` when applied to `(v, 1)` is zero for any `v`. \n\nBut the difference of two linear maps that are equal on a set of generators is zero.\n\nHowever, perhaps we can find `g` using partial derivatives.\n\n### Step 6: Better Approach Using Partial Derivatives\n\nLet‚Äôs compute `fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1)` explicitly. \n\n1. The Fr√©chet derivative is a linear map `(EuclideanSpace ‚ĄĚ (Fin n) √ó ‚ĄĚ) ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ`.\n2. In coordinates, if we write `F(r, t)` as a function, then for any `(v, s) : (EuclideanSpace ‚ĄĚ (Fin n) √ó ‚ĄĚ)`, we have:\n   ```\n   fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, s) = ‚ąĎ i : Fin n, (‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r, t) v_i + s (‚ąāF/‚ąāt)(r, t)\n   ```\n   (This follows from differentiability and the chain rule.)\n3. In particular, `fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1) = ‚ąĎ i : Fin n, (‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r, t) v_i + (‚ąāF/‚ąāt)(r, t)`.\n\nBut by the assumption `h`, for any `r, t, r', t'` and any `v`, we have:\n```\n‚ąĎ i : Fin n, (‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r, t) v_i + (‚ąāF/‚ąāt)(r, t) = ‚ąĎ i : Fin n, (‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r', t') v_i + (‚ąāF/‚ąāt)(r', t')\n```\n\nThis equality must hold for any `v`. \n\nLet‚Äôs compare coefficients:\n\n1. For the zero vector `v = 0`, we get `(‚ąāF/‚ąāt)(r, t) = (‚ąāF/‚ąāt)(r', t')`. That is, the partial derivative w.r.t. `t` is constant (as a function of `r` and `t`). Let‚Äôs call this constant `c`.\n2. Now, for a general `v`, the above becomes `‚ąĎ i (‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r, t) v_i + c = ‚ąĎ i (‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r', t') v_i + c`, so `‚ąĎ i [(‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r, t) - (‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r', t')] v_i = 0`. \n\nBut this must hold for any `v`, which implies that `(‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r, t) = (‚ąāF/‚ąār_i)(r', t')` for any `i : Fin n`. \n\nThat",
