/-!

## A. General Total Time Derivative

-/

/-- A function őīL(r, v, t) is a total time derivative if it can be written as d/dt F(r, t)
    for some function F that depends on position and time but not velocity.

    Mathematically: őīL(r, v, t) = fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1)

    By the chain rule, this equals ‚ąāF/‚ąāt(r, t) + ‚ü®‚ąáŠĶ£F(r, t), v‚ü©.

    This is the most general form of Lagrangian equivalence under total derivatives.
    The key point is that F must be independent of velocity. -/
def IsTotalTimeDerivative {n : ‚Ąē}
    (őīL : EuclideanSpace ‚ĄĚ (Fin n) ‚Üí EuclideanSpace ‚ĄĚ (Fin n) ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ) : Prop :=
  ‚ąÉ (F : EuclideanSpace ‚ĄĚ (Fin n) √ó ‚ĄĚ ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ) (_ : Differentiable ‚ĄĚ F),
    ‚ąÄ r v t, őīL r v t = fderiv ‚ĄĚ F (r, t) (v, 1)

